Top Stories (February 22)

CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR, UTILITIES EXPECTED TO MEET WEDNESDAY ON RESCUE PLAN
California Gov. Gray Davis is expected to meet Wednesday night with 
executives of the state's three investor-owned utilities to negotiate a deal 
to purchase the utilities transmission assets.
http://199.97.97.79/IMDS%PMADJN0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/djn/2001/
02/22/eng-djn/eng-djn_002023_244_759925203398

WILLIAMS ANNOUNCES LONG-TERM POWER AGREEMENT WITH CALIFORNIA
A unit of Williams today announced a 10-year, fixed-price power agreement 
with the California Department of Water Resources to provide up to 1,400 
megawatts of much needed power to California.
http://199.97.97.163/IMDS%PMANAT0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/comtex/2
001/02/22/pr/0000-3477-ok-ca-williams-power

NYISO APPROVES PROCESS TO PREVENT POWER MARKET MANIPULATION
The operator of New York's bulk power grid said Thursday it approved a 
process that will prevent manipulation of the day-ahead power market by 
automatically reviewing and mitigating improper offers.
http://199.97.97.79/IMDS%PMADJN0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/djn/2001/
02/22/eng-djn/eng-djn_210051_191_413916791789

FLORIDA UTILITY REGULATOR FORESEES NO POWER SHORTAGES
A move to deregulate Florida's electric industry hit a bump on Wednesday as 
the state's top utility regulator told a Senate panel there is no power 
shortage in the state and none is projected through the end of this decade.
http://199.97.97.163/IMDS%PMAKRT0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/knightri
dder/2001/02/22/krtbn/0000-0106-FL-ENERGY

-ATLANTA'S SOUTHERN COMPANY TO INCREASE ELECTRIC-GENERATING CAPACITY IN 
SOUTHEAST
Southern Co. outlined plans Tuesday to boost its electric generating capacity 
in the Southeast by 20 percent during the next three years to avoid a 
California-style power shortage.
http://199.97.97.163/IMDS%PMAKRT0%read%/home/content/users/imds/feeds/writersd
esk/2001/02/21/eng-powerm-000001/eng-powerm-000001_235550_160_375711333472

